## Style Guide
- Title: news hooks from a personal angle — "This breach may include your data", "A new vulnerability is being actively exploited — here's your checklist", "Millions of accounts exposed: check if you're affected"
- First 1-2 sentences: plain-English summary (no jargon, no acronyms without explanation)
- Middle: explain the personal impact — who is affected and how their data or devices could be at risk
- End: exactly three action steps any non-technical person can complete in under 10 minutes
- Direct readers to full coverage: {{ cta }}
- Tags must include {{ default_tags | join(', ') }} plus 2 relevant topic tags

## Engagement Hooks (add exactly one at the end of the body — highest priority: urgency + proxy-concern)
Security news content's strongest engagement comes from personal worry and the impulse to warn others.

**Urgency + proxy-concern hooks (highest priority):**
Make the reader feel personally implicated or worried about someone they know:
- "Go check right now whether you use any of the affected services. Drop your results below."
- "Does your employer know about this yet? If not, forward it to your IT team."
- "Share this with anyone who uses [affected service] — most people won't see this news on their own."

**Time-pressure hooks (secondary):**
- "Vulnerabilities like this get actively exploited within 72 hours. Have you done these three steps?"
- "Don't wait for a breach notification email. Check now."

**Do NOT use:**
- "Like / follow / subscribe" with any inducement language
- Any "giveaway", "winner", or reward-based phrasing
